# Node Tooling (vs .NET CLI)

| .NET | Node |
|------|------|
| `dotnet new` | `npm init`, starter templates, or clone repo |
| `dotnet restore` | `npm install` |
| `dotnet add package X` | `npm install X` |
| `dotnet run` | `npm start` or `node dist/index.js` |
| `dotnet build` | `tsc` (TypeScript compile) |
| `dotnet test` | `npm test` (vitest/jest) |
| `*.csproj` | `package.json` |
| `nuget.config` | `.npmrc` |
| Solution / projects | monorepo (optional); usually single `package.json` |

## package.json Scripts

```json
{
  "scripts": {
    "dev": "tsx watch src/index.ts",
    "build": "tsc",
    "start": "node dist/index.js"
  }
}
```

## Key Files

- `package.json` — dependencies + scripts (like csproj + Program.cs entry)
- `package-lock.json` — lock file (commit it; like packages.lock.json)
- `node_modules/` — restored packages (like NuGet cache + local refs; **gitignore**)
- `tsconfig.json` — TypeScript compiler options (like LangVersion + nullable settings)

## ESM vs CJS

- `"type": "module"` → use `import`/`export`; file extensions matter (`.js` in imports after compile).
- Without it → CommonJS `require()` (legacy; many AI SDK examples still use it).
